’s Performance of Gender and Authorship -- tIV Transformations: Women Writing in the New Century -- tIntroduction -- t12 From Frauenliteratur to Frauenliteraturbetrieb: Marketing Literature to German Women in the Twenty-First Century -- t13 Social Alienation and Gendered Surveillance: Julia Franck Observes Post-Wende Society -- t14 Small Stories: The Novels of Martina Hefter -- t15 The Young Author as Public Intellectual: The Case of Juli Zeh -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhile the first decade after the fall of the Berlin wall was marked by the challenges of unification and the often difficult process of reconciling East and West German experiences, many Germans expected that the “new century” would achieve “normalization.” The essays in this volume take a closer look at Germany’s new normalcy and argue for a more nuanced picture that considers the ruptures as well as the continuities. Germany’s new generation of writers is more diverse than ever before, and their texts often not only speak of a Germany that is multicultural but also take a more playful attitude toward notions of identity. Written with an eye toward similar and dissimilar developments and traditions on both sides of the Atlantic, this volume balances overviews of significant trends in present-day cultural life with illustrative analyses of individual writers and texts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aGerman literaturexAppreciationzEurope, German-speaking. 0aGerman literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGerman literaturezEurope, German-speakingxHistory and criticism. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Germany.2bisacsh1 aAnderson, Donovan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.lo